@node Requirements " Requirements "


                            ****************
                              Requirements
                            ****************

 Seek was compiled with SAS/C-compiler v6.5 on an Amiga 500
 Kickstart V37.175, Workbench V38.35 with 4MB memory + 80MB harddisk.

 Hopefully it'll work on any Amiga as long as it has Kickstart 37++, but if
 it doesn't, please @{"let me know" link BugReports}.

@endnode
@node Introduction " Introduction "


                            ****************
                              Introduction
                            ****************

 Are you one of those who copy files to your harddisk and then forget where
 you put them. Don't feel like you're the only one. My memory too, is very
 useful but sadly very short.
 No need to worry anymore. Your problem (and mine for that matter) is now
 solved. The solution is Seek (what else?).

 Going through my old sourcecodes I found this program and decided to make
 some improvements.
 As you might have seen there are many programs like this one but none of
 them can do what Seek does.

 Seek was mainly written to search for files, but I soon discovered that just
 finding the files weren't enough. Many programs doesn't have the ability to
 look through a directory tree to find files. I therefor added the option to
 execute any command on the files it find. This makes it possible to
 eg. delete all files matching '#?.bak' on a whole volume.
 What you want to do with the files Seek finds is up to you but deleting
 them could be one of them. The only requirement is that the command you
 execute must not expect any input (besides commandline arguments of course).

 Seek will find both files and directories matching the pattern.
 Files are printed in black and directories in blue.
@endnode
@node Options " Commandline options "

 Here are the valid arguments for Seek.

  Seek PATTERN/A,PATH/M,CMD/K,ICONS/S,NOREQ/S,ASK/S

   PATTERN - (required)
             The pattern that the files must match. Any AmigaDOS pattern is
             valid. See your AmigaDOS manual for more information about
             pattern matching.

   PATH    - (optional)
             Where Seek should start to look for the files. All its sub-
             directories will be searched too. If no path is given, Seek
             will look in the current directory and its subdirectories.
             You may enter more then one path.

   CMD     - (optional)
             The command to execute on files found. If the commandstring
             contains spaces, you must enter it within quotation marks (").
             Replace the filename with %s in the commandstring. %s will
             before execution, be replaced with the filename including it's
             path.

   ICONS   - (optional)
             As default, no icons will be found even if they match the
             pattern. Using this switch, they will be found.

   NOREQ   - (optional)
             If you enter a unit that isn't mounted, a requester will popup
             asking you to put it in any drive. This option will supress
             the requester and exit the program with an error.

   ASK     - (optional in conjuncion with CMD)
             If this option is entered, a question is asked whether or not
             you want to execute the command. This question understand four
             answers. They are: Yes, No, All, Quit.

              Yes  - Execute command.
              No   - Do not execute command.
              All  - Execute command on all files found. No more questions.
              Quit - Do not execute command and quit.

             You may either answer with the full word or just the first
             letter. Answers that doesn't match the above, will be taken
             as a No.

 In case you didn't understand, here's some examples.

 Example 1:

  Seek #?.bak DH0: DH1: CMD "delete %s"

  This will delete all files on DH0: and DH1: that ends with '.bak'.


 Example 2:

  Seek #?.c DH0: CMD "copy %s df0:" ASK

  This will copy all files on DH0: that ends with '.c', but before the
  command is executed, Seek will ask if you want to execute the command
  (in this case copy the file).

 Example 3:

  Seek a#?z CMD "s:script %s"

  This will start a script in s: when a file that starts with 'a' and ends
  with 'z', is found. This script could for example copy the file to another
  directory, then archive the file and finally delete it. By using scripts
  you can execute several commands on the files you find.
  The only limit is your imagination.
@endnode
@node VersionNotes " Seek version notes "

 Since this is the first help-doc I make on this command and it has gone
 more than a year since I last made any changes to Seek, it's a bit
 difficult to sum them up, but from now on I'm going to keep track of them.

 Version          Changes
 =======          =======

  5.0             Added possibility to execute any CLI-based command on found
                  files.

  5.1             Removed a bug that caused Seek to execute a command even if
                  no commandstring was given.
                  The old version didn't change to black textcolor after
                  printing with blue color. This has been fixed.

  5.2             Seek could, if no path was given, enter an infinite loop.

@endnode
